segments.text: Academia was always a real shame, I thought.
But gosh, I'm trying to think of what the people, what his nickname was in the class.
Well, he was in his own stratus.
As you look back, who were some of the most important teachers and the most important courses in forming
What you became as a veterinarian.
The course in pathology, of course, was not surprisingly with Hilton Smith.
Hilton Smith was a, he just blew me away.
And of course, Dr. John was important while I was a student.
But I'd say that Dr. John's, my view of him really developed even further
when he was my department head as an employee.
But Dr. Smith was such a broadly knowledgeable individual.
And so he was
I guess the most influential single person.

Al Price was still, I have to think of Al Price as having a big influence on me because he just, you know, I think of him as the guy that if you think about one of these spirited horses, not that I was that spirited, but a horse that's kind of trying his reins all the time.
And then somebody comes along with an air of authority and jerks on those reins just one time, you know, and gets his attention.
Well, Al Price jerked on the reins for me.
All right.
Did Dr. Smith plant a pathology seed in your heart and mind?
Yeah.
To be that knowledgeable of disease, he's the one who introduced me to,
disease is a subject matter.
And that's when I began, that was the beginning then of my deteriorating vision of large animals.
Because I had a new love, I guess.
Did you talk this over with anybody?
This change in, this change of feeling?
It happened.
over, I wouldn't say that I discussed the pros and cons of it.
I talked with Dr. Smith from time to time.
And he presented, I was one of the people that persuaded him to teach an elective course, which he'd never done.
That was the only time he ever taught an elective course in just large animal pathology.
And I got enough of my classmates to take it so it could be offered.
But just interacting with him on kind of learning how he ticked, just what made him go.
by talking with him in class and so on.
His labs were just a total fascination to me, the way he would handle students.
He was a very mild-mannered person, and he was embarrassed when he embarrassed a student, but he would still do it.
Now, what year was that class?
Sophomore, second year.
Second year.

was there any uh during the first or second year were there any supposed roadblocks where if somebody was going to flunk out that it normally happened at this point or drop out it normally happened well the the uh gross anatomy course with gibbs always caught some and that was what year second that was a spring of the first year of the first year okay um
And usually there'd be one or two in biochemistry.
And you never had any thought about driving out of vet school and going to some other profession?
Not seriously.
I did think about it, though, because I had a couple of my really good friends that did that.
My best friend, who I thought regarded as my best friend, was a man by the name of Giles Shannon, who
whose father had always wanted him to be a physician, and yet he wanted to be a veterinarian.
And his dad died shortly after we got into vet school, or shortly after we started vet school, and he decided that he wouldn't change at that point.
So you thought about it briefly?
And I thought about it at that time and decided, no, if I had, you know...
I'm not sure what I would do now.
I think as I reflected on it subsequently in latter years, it would have been a lot easier to do the things that I have done professionally if I had gone to medical school.
If you had a serious item to discuss when you were in vet school, was there anybody you went to for advice and counsel?

well no one there was not a system set up for us now we had a we had a new physiology teacher by the name of Ed McMurray he had just come he came back and we were the first class he taught and he was a an individual that

people just kind of migrated to and of course you know this was a real gift for him and he he began to do that and that was really his life calling I think to to be a counselor and but he was not putting himself forth that way for us and
We had, I had a classmate, one of my older classmates was really the father figure for our class, for the younger ones, Bill Kirksey is his name.
K-I-R-K-S-E-Y.
Bill is retired now, but he had a career in practice in Fort Worth.
So y'all would go to him for...

His wife, Clara, was the first librarian in the vet school, and she actually had that job as a student position, kind of a student-level position at the beginning, but she was the first librarian for the vet school.
And when that year ends, you have done well and you're pleased, is that right?
Mm-hmm.
And what did you do that summer?
Back to the oil field.
Back to the oil field.
Then you come back as a sophomore.
Had much changed?
Was it you felt good that you were on the right track?
Yeah, I was totally caught up in it.
what I was studying and everything.
I mean, I was preparing, you know, very satisfied with my career choice.
And Dean Price was not yet, he was not yet, Al Price was not yet the dean.
No, that happened after I graduated in the, see, I went on the faculty to the big enticement for,
really was that I would be able to work under Al Price.
And that lasted for two months.
And then he became dean.
And you're beginning to, are you beginning to think about pathology as a sophomore?
Well, that happened in the, I would say that was in the, toward the end of that second year.
that I began to think, well, you know, this wouldn't be a bad thing to do.
Were there any special courses or teachers you had that second year?
Well, Hilton Smith.
Hilton Smith.
In the spring, we had Dick Turk.
In the fall, we had Rural Bells.
Dick Turk was on sabbatical.
R.D.
Turk?
Yeah.
What was his nickname?
Did you all have a nickname for him?
Hmm.
No, there have been some, but I don't, we didn't, we were so pleased to have him.
He was something else, you know.
Now, I gather.
P.W.
Burns, we had, of course, Pappy Burns was our physiology teacher.
Now, Ed McMurray came in then in the spring and started teaching.
He taught the physiology in the spring, and then that freed Dr. Burns up to teach toxicology, which was then a third year course.
And so we only had him for one semester.
Was there any encouragement for you all to go home in the summer and do something specifically related to veterinary medicine?
No, it wasn't.
It was after your third year.
There was quite a lot of emphasis, I guess, placed on that.
Yeah, I went to work in Wichita Falls at the big practice.
It was one of the plums, and I was very fortunate to... And it was a mixed practice?
Mixed practice, uh-huh.
And you say big.
How many veterinarians?
Two veterinarians, but they...
two owners, Barrington and Dewey.
But they typically would work one or two others.
And then after my time there and later, well, by the 60s, I think that was a four or five-man practice.
Now, by and large, in that era, veterinarians were single practice operations generally?
Yeah.
That was the most common mode, I'd say.
And if more than one, it would be two.
You rarely saw a three or four person practice.
And that was the case in Houston as well.
When you saw multiple.
people practice, it would be two people.
How soon did you students begin to get pretty sure in the large or small animal practice goal?
There were a few students who came in from, like the Houston folk, all but one of them, there was one of them that was equine and the others were
They came wanting to be, their model was a small animal practitioner and that's what they wanted to be.
But except for that group and maybe there were a couple from Fort Worth who came out of a small animal practice background and wanted it.
But other than that,
I'd say most of us were kind of mixed orientation and keeping your options open.
That was a common term.
Were there many who were dreaming of going into industrial research or anything?
Uh-uh.
And were there any that during those four years of vet school, were there any of y'all that were dreaming of being an academic?
Mm-mm.
I wasn't at all.
See, mine all happened with Armistead.
I went in to speak with Armistead because I knew that he had, not very many years before that, he had done a PhD.
And so I thought he would be a likely resource person.
I'd seen this flyer from Purdue about,

graduate assistantships for veterinarians who wanted to do a graduate study and and it was the way it was written it was obvious that they were basically working on livestock diseases and now but this was in my senior year that I saw that and got it twicked my curiosity a little bit and so I went to see
farmer said, just to talk to him about that.
What would you do if I were to go to that and do that and get another degree, what would I do then?
And so that's... What did he say?
What was his answer?
Well, he said that he told me about some of the opportunities that there would be to
work in the field of research like with pharmaceutical firms or go to work for the government or go into academia.
And that was what year?
That was my fourth year.
And then he kind of did a big however.
He just happened to have this
opening that he had developed and he was very interested in and he had set this up because there was as a way to to allow young veterinarians to learn about academic veterinary medicine and
He thought I would be a good candidate for that.
Now, did he invite you, or did you go to see him?
Well, I went to see him about the Purdue thing.
I asked for an appointment and saw him.
But then he turned the tables.
Academically, you were second in your class?
No, I was fourth, I think.
Okay.
Now, and with that, with these grades being posted, by and large, did...
Did people have a kind of a ranking for each class?
Yeah, well, I don't know how many of my classmates would have known where I was.
Everyone knew that Wallace Klebb was the top.
Okay.
And Bill Kirksey was probably the second.
Did they know that there were also a few that were down right at the bottom?
Yeah.
And were there some who were in jeopardy almost every semester?
Yeah.
Is that?
Yeah.
Just skim by.
But those guys didn't care for the most part.
And did y'all have a, as you went through, did the feeling of class pride and pulling together, did that
Oh yeah, that was very strong in our class.
How did you all help each other?
Give some examples of where the class helped each other, either academically or when there was a personal crisis or whatever.
Well, whenever one of the, we would work with the students who were
would be having problems and would get into trouble and would be flunking a course, for example.
You all would help them with the homework and study in the lab?
We were, this was pretty common with, now Cleb didn't do very much of that.
It wasn't that he wasn't willing to, but he was a very, he was a stoic individual.
And he just wasn't able to help.
He tried a number of times, but it didn't take, because he didn't know what to tell people or what to say to them.
And we had some others of us that were kind of part-time tutors, I guess, for students.
Do you remember any crises where
somebody had a tragedy or an illness or an injury that somebody helped with?
What about somebody that ended up short of money?
Did anybody help?
Did you lend it to anybody?
Well, that was just part of life at the time.
Yeah, there were some.
helping out along that line that went on.
And among the most feared courses in the four years were what?
Supposedly the toughest, and you were glad to get them done.
Well, that gross anatomy course was one.
A lot of students
worried about the embryology course that Al Price taught, because it was very challenging.
And then the toxicology course that Dr. Burns taught was probably, if you were to poll my classmates, that's probably the course that would be listed, be between that and the gross anatomy course.
It was a surgery course that was pretty intimidating, but it was so interesting that nobody shied away from it.
Looking back on all four years, what do you wish there had been more of and perhaps less of?
If you've only got four years to do it, was there any modification in hindsight?

Well there were from at the time that I finished I had a feeling that the public health courses were had been a pretty much a waste of time and that there I would have wished to have been able to substitute in some

disease courses on the disease of the animal more in depth on that but you know that very much reflects the bias that I had in those courses at least one of those courses was very important that in that time that the public health course because a large I say a large I mean there were several of my classmates that at one time or another worked in the brucellosis eradication program
And there are several of them that have made substantial contributions to the USDA program.
Is there anything you didn't do enough of?
Yeah.
Given that there were only four years and it had to be

again at the time that I finished I guess my feeling was it would have been I really wish there had been more opportunity to have hands on experience with cases we didn't have we weren't put in a position of responsibility very well we would be like with in small animal for example we'd be

we were exposed to the cases and we did and we held animals and things like that but we we there was only one of the small animal clinicians I thought that was really very good at trying to draw out the thoughts of the students on pieces and not to the extent I mean our people now I just marvel of course you know in the

I worked not as a clinician, but there among the clinicians in the position that I had after I was department head, and as I had before I was department head, being kind of the hospital pathologist, if you will.
And I just marvel at the...
job that those people do in involving the students.
They really do a good job now.
Looking at those four years, what did A&M do best and what did it do worst in veterinary medicine then?
Or at least best, maybe I can phrase that in a positive way.

best was would have been the equine work working with horses equine medicine and equine surgery and also livestock medicine at that time with cattle particularly we did much more of that then it was a much larger segment of of the
hospital operation than it is now.
And that's not to say anything against the present hospital.
It's just society now in a way.
We have so many more private practitioners now.
There were virtually none in this community when I was in vet school.
I think our education was very, very tailored.
It was very much tailored to prepare us for a practice career.
We had...
There was nothing done to make us aware of non-practice opportunities.
And I think it's really...

amazing that as many of my my class and the class of classes around me that wound up doing things other than practices probably kind of remarkable but it would have been uh much better if we could have had some exposure to our to the other well research for example but there were there wasn't
There were very few research programs that were funded.
There was very little money, research money, in the vet school at the time I was in vet school.
As far as you were aware, you and your friends, your classmates at that time, how did A&M's veterinary program compare nationally?
Where did you all think it ranked?
Well, we felt it was one of the good ones.
We didn't know.
This was not a point of very much concern to us.
That's what I was going to say.
I'll bet there wasn't much discussion then of that.
No, it just wasn't an item to think about or worry about.
Did anybody ever discuss, any of you veterinary students, ever discuss women attending this program and or black students?
Never talked about the absence of either one.
That's what I would have guessed.
And we didn't, I guess we, our view of veterinary medicine was
pretty chauvinistic, I guess.
But it wasn't a matter of seeing it as something that males were deserving of.
It was just the occupation was just kind of a hazardous sort of a thing.
It's like women playing football.
Of course, now it has evolved just so much in the other direction.
Now, I've just about run out of questions.
Are there some important topics we haven't touched?
Well, nothing that occurs to me.
I wasn't particularly, well, let's see.
As you look back, were there any funny, goofy, humorous events you can recall during those four years?
Let students ever play a joke on one of the faculty?
Other than those you mentioned a while ago on Gibbs?
Oh, well, when we moved, I worked for Physiology Department.

Dr. Burns had set up, during that era, had set up two or three student positions for students that were in their third year in vet school after they'd finished their second year when they had physiology.
Well, then they were student assistants.
I can't remember if it was two or four students that he did.
two or four positions.
But anyway, he had some positions.
And I was able to get one of those.
And there must have been four of us involved.
But we were involved then in moving physiology from the main campus out to the buildings across the tracks.
One of the guys, he was not in one of those positions, but a guy by the name of Helms.
He was a classmate of mine who was working, I guess, on hourly wages just to help move stuff out.
And Dr. Burns had a supply.
He had containers of unadulterated
absolute alcohol that he was very protective of, as he should have been.
And he left the container open, well, the cabinet unlocked one day.
And old Helms got into that and got some out of the pharmacy.
He found some of the tincture of cherry syrup or something like that for flavoring.
He just had a party out there.
Now that wasn't a prank on Dr. Burns, but boy, it really infuriated him, because he fell down the stairs.
He was so inebriated that he fell down the stairs.
But earlier, the thing that was a prank that turned out
